# Chat commands (git → copy-paste text)

When the user’s message is **only** or **primarily** one of the phrases below, treat it as a request to **run git locally**, **inspect the result**, and **reply with ready-to-paste text** in **fenced code blocks** (so they can copy in one click). Use complete sentences in titles/bodies; no filler.

## Commit message helpers (`cm`)

**Never create commits:** for any `cm` command, use **read-only** git (`diff`, `log`, `status`, etc.) only. **Do not** run `git commit`, `git add`, `git merge`, `git rebase`, or anything that writes history or the index on the user’s behalf. The developer commits locally after copying your message.

| Phrase      | Inspect |
|------------|---------|
| `cm staged` | `git diff --staged` (cached/index only) |
| `cm unstaged` | `git diff` (working tree vs index) |
| `cm full` | **both**: staged first, then unstaged (two diffs or clearly labeled sections) |

**Trunk detection (for `cm` output):** resolve the default branch name via `git symbolic-ref refs/remotes/origin/HEAD` (e.g. `refs/remotes/origin/master` → `master`), or fall back to **`main`** / **`master`** whichever exists. Compare to `git branch --show-current`.

**Ticket prefix from branch (`EVO-*`):** when producing `cm` output, use the current branch name from `git branch --show-current`. If it contains a ticket id matching **`EVO-` + digits** (first match of the pattern `EVO-\d+`, case-sensitive), prefix the **subject line** with **`[<match>]`** and a space—for example **`[EVO-55]`**. Examples:

- On trunk: `[EVO-55] feat: restore exercise position from URL`
- Off trunk: `[EVO-55] Restore exercise position from URL`

If the branch name has no such match, omit the prefix. The **≤72 character** limit applies to the **entire** subject line **including** the bracket prefix.

**Output:** One **markdown code block** containing a **proposed git commit message**. If there is nothing to commit for that scope, say so and do not fabricate a message.

### When the current branch **is** the default trunk (`master` / `main`)

Use a **Conventional Commit–style subject**: **`<type>: <imperative title>`** (≤72 chars for the whole line; lowercase `type`), **after** any **`[EVO-…]`** prefix when the branch rule above applies—e.g. **`[EVO-55] feat: imperative title`**. Pick the best-fitting `type`, for example:

| `type` | Use for |
|--------|--------|
| `chore` | Tooling, deps, config, Cursor rules, housekeeping |
| `feat` | New user-facing behavior or capability (“feature”) |
| `fix` | Bug fixes |
| `test` | Tests only |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `refactor` | Internal structure without behavior change |
| `perf` | Performance |
| `ci` | CI config |
| `build` | Build system / bundler |
| `style` | Formatting, whitespace (no logic change) |

Then a **blank line**, then the **description** as **bullet points** (`- ` lines)—each bullet a short, complete sentence.

Example shape: `chore: add Cursor rules for agent chat commands` then bullets.

**Note:** Squashed PR merges onto trunk often use a different message from the merge UI; this **`type: title` + bullets** format is for **direct commits on trunk** you craft locally. Do not force this format when the current branch is **not** trunk.

### When the current branch is **not** the default trunk

Subject line: **imperative mood**, no required `type:` prefix (feature-branch workflow), **after** any **`[EVO-…]`** prefix when the branch rule above applies. Blank line, then the same **bullet** body as above.

## PR helpers (`pr`)

**Never mutate git or GitHub remotely:** for any `pr` command, use **read-only** git (`log`, `diff`, `status`, etc.) only. **Do not** run `git push`, `git commit`, or open/update PRs via CLI or API (`gh pr create`, etc.). The developer pushes and opens the PR after copying your text.

Base branch: use **`origin/HEAD`** if available; otherwise **`origin/master`** or **`origin/main`** (whichever exists in the repo). If the current branch **is** the base or there are no unique commits, say so clearly.

**Scope of history:** describe work **unique to this branch**, not the whole first-parent history of `base` after a merge-from-base. Use:

```text
git merge-base <base> HEAD   # optional; three-dot uses this internally
git log --oneline --first-parent <base>..HEAD
git diff <base>...HEAD
```

`--first-parent` keeps the commit list on the branch’s mainline (merges from `base` into the branch do not flood the list with foreign commits). **`git diff <base>...HEAD`** (three dots) is the net PR diff from the merge-base to `HEAD`. Prefer summarizing that net change set.

| Phrase       | Output |
|-------------|--------|
| `pr title`  | One **code block**: a single PR **title** line (GitHub title field). |
| `pr changes`| One **code block**: PR **description** body in **GitHub-flavored Markdown** (summary, key changes, testing notes if relevant). |
| `pr full`   | **Two** code blocks in order: (1) title — one line, (2) description — markdown body. Label them e.g. `PR title` / `PR description` in prose above the blocks so the user knows which is which. |

If there is no diff vs base, state that instead of inventing content.
